{
  "text": "During the experiments, the thermos for DNA denaturation can maintain its temperature between 98 and 93\u00b0C. At this temperature range, DNA can be rapidly denatured. Melting curve analyses of PCR amplicons have demonstrated that most DNA or PCR amplicons melt/ denature completely at 90\u00b0C and below [CITATION_1] , therefore, the slight temperature drop throughout the duration of the PCR reaction will not prohibit denaturation and the subsequent annealing of primers to the denatured DNA.",
  "citation_candidates": [
